    },
    "body": "When an STF `stream_ctx` is constructed from a user stream that is already capturing (e.g. opened by `cudaStreamBeginCapture(..., Relaxed)` or `wp.ScopedCapture`), two problems prevented task submission from completing the capture cleanly:\r\n\r\n1. In `task::acquire`, the context's `start_events` were only merged as prerequisites when the task had *zero* dependencies. A task with only `write()`-mode dependencies has no *input* predecessor and therefore was never linked to the context's start event. The first pool stream picked for such a task was then synchronized via `cudaStreamWaitEvent` against an event that was never recorded inside the capture, producing `cudaErrorStreamCaptureIsolation` at submission or finalize time.\r\n\r\n   Fix: compute a `has_input_dep` flag in the existing dependency loop (true for `read` / `rw` / `reduce` / `relaxed` accesses, including after mode merging). If the task has no input dependency and the context has start events, merge them as prerequisites. This makes every task's first pool stream fork from the user stream inside the capture, so its subsequent work is correctly captured.\r\n\r\n2. Passing a user-supplied `async_resources_handle` together with a capturing user stream is still unsafe: the handle's pool very likely carries streams with residual uncaptured work from prior contexts, and CUDA will reject folding them into the ongoing capture. Reject this configuration early with a clear `EXPECT` message.\r\n\r\nTo implement the check cleanly without losing move semantics on the handle, `backend_ctx_untyped::impl` now records `user_provided_handle = bool(async_resources)` in its member initializer list *before* the handle is moved in. `stream_ctx(cudaStream_t, async_resources_handle)` then inspects `state().user_provided_handle` in its body and, if set, asserts that `user_stream` is not currently capturing.\r\n\r\nAdds `cudax/test/stf/local_stf/legacy_to_stf_in_capture.cu`, which runs a diamond-DAG workload twice under an explicit `cudaStreamBeginCapture` in relaxed mode -- once with hand-wired event-based dependencies, once through `stream_ctx` + tokens -- compares the instantiated graphs, validates the host-side result, and also checks that constructing `stream_ctx(capture_stream, handle)` during an active capture triggers the new assertion.\r\n\r\nMade-with: Cursor\r\n\r\n## Description\r\n\r\n<!-- Every PR should have a corresponding issue that describes and motivates the work done in the PR -->\r\ncloses <!-- Link issue here -->\r\n\r\n<!-- Provide a standalone description of changes in this PR. -->\r\n\r\n<!-- Note: The pull request title will be included in the CHANGELOG. -->\r\n\r\n## Checklist\r\n<!-- TODO: - [ ] I am familiar with the [Contributing Guidelines](). -->\r\n- [x] New or existing tests cover these changes.\r\n- [x] The documentation is up to date with these changes.\r\n",
